{
  "answer": "Manusmrti chapter 5 and Visnu Smriti chapter 51 share a substantial common core on food rules—both permit the same five ritual fish (Pathina, Rohita, Rajiva, Simhatunda, scaly fish / Sakula), the same five-toed animals (hare, porcupine, iguana, rhinoceros, tortoise), and both close with identical or near-identical verses equating sacrifice-killing with non-killing. However, Manu's vegetarian leaning pushes past Visnu in three identifiable ways:\n\n1. **Francolin partridge explicitly forbidden vs. explicitly permitted.** Manu ch.5 v.12 (Mn_5.12, p-2e26d0) lists the francolin partridge in its roster of forbidden birds. Visnu Smriti ch.51 v.31 (Vi_51.31, p-389844) explicitly exempts the francolin from any penance—treating it as a permitted bird alongside partridge, quail, and peacock. This is the sharpest direct contradiction between the two texts on permitted flesh.\n\n2. **Peacock permitted by Visnu, not by Manu.** Visnu Smriti 51.31 names the peacock as an explicitly permitted bird (no penance for eating it). Manu chapter 5 provides no such permission for peacock, and its general rule (Mn_5.17, p-2f8c39)—'one should not eat unknown beasts and birds'—leans toward restriction for anything not affirmatively listed.\n\n3. **Manu's rhetorical escalation on fish.** Manu 5.15 (p-9ac8b8) deploys a categorical maxim: 'an eater of fish is an eater of all meat; therefore, one should avoid fish.' Visnu Smriti 51.21 prescribes only a three-night fast for eating non-permitted fish, without any equivalent rhetorical condemnation. Both texts permit the same ritual fish, but Manu frames even that permission as a concession embedded in a general principle of fish-avoidance, while Visnu merely grades penances.\n\nIn sum, the clearest food Visnu allows but Manu forbids is the francolin partridge. More broadly, Manu frames non-ritual meat eating as 'demonic law' (Mn_5.31, p-db3fdb) and positions fish-eating as morally equivalent to eating all flesh—rhetorical moves that push his code toward vegetarianism beyond Visnu's penance-calibrated permissiveness.",
